0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he advantages </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of a levy far outweigh the disadvantages. A levy could be used to support farmland that generates sustainable food production and contributes to landscape scale action and ecosystem services. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">BASC proposes three theme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s for the guiding principles to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">retailers. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">These are (a) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">looking after </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">England’s nature, (b) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">landscape scale</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> action and ecosystem services and (c) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">supporting sustainable food production.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">BASC’s proposals link global, European and domestic policy and could help address gaps in funding that prevent implementation of those policies.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The disadvantages of the levy are minimal, as demonstrated in Northern Ireland and Wales where the levy already exists.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">About BASC</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">BASC was founded in 1908 and is the UK’s largest shooting association with a growing membership of 134,000.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">BASC aims to promote and protect sporting shooting and the well-being of the countryside throughout the UK and overseas.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">BASC believes that all who shoot should conduct themselves according to the highest standards of safety, sportsmanship and courtesy, with full respect for their quarry and a practical interest in wildlife conservation.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The total value of sporting shooting to the UK economy in 2004 was £1.6 billion.  (Source 2006. PACEC. Economic and Environmental Impact of Sporting Shooting in the UK.  Available online at </span><a href="http://www.shootingfacts.co.uk"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">www.shootingfacts.co.uk</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. This study will be repeated in 2014 and we expect to see significant increases to the above figures. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Every year </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">people who shoot</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> spend £250 million on conservation, in comparison the RSPB’s net income la</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">st year was just £89 million. Shooters</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> spend 2.7 million days on conservation – the equivalent of 12,000 full-time jobs. That is more than the 10,000 permanent employee</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s at Defra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. The wildlife trusts manage 93,000 hectares, RSPB </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">reserves cover 165,000 hectares and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">people who shoot</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> manage 2,000,000 hectares as a home for nature – an area the size of Wales.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (Source 2006. PACEC. Economic and Environmental Impact of Sporting Shooting in the UK.  Available online at </span><a href="http://www.shootingfacts.co.uk"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">www.shootingfacts.co.uk</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. This study will be repeated in 2014 and we expect to see significant increases to the above figures. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">P</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">eople who shoot are actively engaged in conservation work. This not only benefits quarry species but also a wide range of other wildlife. BASC’s Green Shoots programme demonstrates how shooting contributes to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the government’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">biodiv</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ersity targets at a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> landscape scale. For more information see: </span><a href="http://basc.org.uk/conservation/green-shoots/"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">http://basc.org.uk/conservation/green-shoots/</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">BASC’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Green Shoots programme is endorsed by Natural England, Environment Agency, Natural Environment Wales, Scottish Natural Heritage, and Northern Ireland Environment Agency.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">BASC Green Shoots in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Cheshire </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">has</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> connected 32km of woodland and hedgerow allowing dormice and other species to extend their range and migrate northwards in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> response to climate change.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> BASC</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> funded this through the landfill communities fund (SITA Trust) and gained access to the f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">armed land primarily through BASC</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> members shooting over it.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">BASC members are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">helping the farmers manage the habitat into the future, thereby securing a long-term legacy post-project.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">BASC Green Shoots in Somerset has</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">helped </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">water voles</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> recover from near extinction.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Building on this success BASC is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">expand</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ing its</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> network of effective mink control </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and the creation of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">suitable habitat for water voles</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Dorset and Devon</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. This will meet the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Environment Agency’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">objective to create</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a mink free habitat rich refuge for water voles in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">west country.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">his landscape scale </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">action is funded by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">statutory agencies and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> SITA Trust, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the landfill communities’ fund.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">BASC Green Shoots will help the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Natural Environment White Paper (NEWP) and the Engl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and Biodiversity Strategy (EBS) meet their objectives.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Submission</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">BASC’s submission focuses on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">“The relative advantages and disadvantages of the proposed levy rather than a possible complete ban on lightweight plastic bags”. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The major advantage of the proposed levy is that it generates funds for good works.  In Wales, the Welsh Government</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> has</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> issued voluntary guidance to retailers collecting the levy.  This encourages net profits to be spent on environmental causes and particularly welcomes initiatives that benefit local communities.  This has resulted in the majority of monies be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> directed towards </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">environmental charities.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">BASC </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">believes that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the English levy could build on this system to encourage funds to be spent on the core, but underfunded, conservation priorities highlighted under the Natural Environment White Paper (NEWP) and the England Biodiversity Strategy (EBS)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  BASC’s vision is that the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> guidance </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">would provide </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the focus without restricting the range of groups and organisations that could utilise the funds. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">BASC will be responding to the Defra call for evidence on the proposed plastic bag charge for England. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> BASC </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">will be recommending themes for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">guiding principles </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on how </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">retailers </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">may allocate the profits from the levy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">BASC proposes three themes for the guiding principles to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">retailers. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">These are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(a) looking after England’s nature, (b) landscape scale action and ecosystem services and (c) supporting sustainable food production.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Looking after England’s nature</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  B</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">iodiversity underpins ecosystem services and has its own targets </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">arising </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">from the Conve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ntion on Biological Diversity which are supported through the NEWP and EBS. This these will allow for a wide range of projects to be supported.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Landscape scale action and ecosystem services.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  Working at the landscape scale is the primary challenge and priority for conservation in England.  Encouraging support for this type of work is essential.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Supporting sustainable food production</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Producing more food</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> sustainably and whilst delivering environmental benefits is t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he key challenge in the farming, land management and conservation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sector</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Funding work that supports this would make sense both to the consumer paying the charge when shopping for food and be attractive to retailers to promote the sustaina</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">bility of their supply chain.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">BASC’s proposals link global, European and domestic policy and could help address gaps in funding that prevent implementation of those policies.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The impact of the common agricultural policy review </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">will mean much less funding being available for farmed land</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> from 2014.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> BASC has responded to the Defra CAP implementation consultation and was</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> supportive of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">proposals </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to target the funds under pillar two</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, i.e. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">site specific agreements (SSSI), area specific agreements supporting landscape scale activities and, perhaps, a small capit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">al grants scheme.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> However, the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">bulk of the decreased </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">CAP </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">budget will be required to honour existing HLS agreements meaning the funds for new work will be extremely limited.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">One major source of funding for environmental work is the landfill communities fund (LCF).  Recently HMRC directed LCF distributors to spend the majority of the funds allocated to them within the year.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> This change means that securing funding for multi-year projects</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is difficult. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">decrease in grant </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">budgets from statutory agencies also means less funding being available for conservation projects. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The disadvantages 